            "answer_text": "This question is interesting, and textbooks give answers to this, but they conflict and they are usually wrong. There are different theories which state different things. For example quantum electrodynamics has each photon partially absorbed and partially re-emitted an infinite number of times by electrons in the mirror. Wave theory has the incoming wave induce oscillations in countless electrons which then cancel the original wave and emit a wave in new directions. It is not actually possible to experimentally detect photons being absorbed and re-emitted or changing direction and energy. (Talking about normal linear optics. We can observe photons absorbed and re-emitted in fluorescence and stimulated emission.) Since momentum is transferred, the reflected photon has a slightly different energy than the incident photon. (There is is special case where the reflecting surface has exactly the same but opposite sign momentum of the photon and the momenta cancel.) People make assertions about this, but what they say depends on which textbook they used. Quantum mechanics does not allow questions like this to be definitely answered. This is closely related to the double slit experiment. How does a quantum particle interfere with itself and be in two places at once, and is it the same particle after it does this? Again, there is no experiment that can answer the question. We have to accept that quantum particles behave in ways that are difficult to comprehend, and if they are indistinguishable, they act as if they are the same particle. It defies our expectations. In the same way, we can\u2019t answer exactly what happens to the photon at the atomic level. Is the reflected photon the same photon or is it a new photon? Again quantum mechanics says that these questions at the atomic level are ultimately meaningless and can not be answered definitively. People may passionately argue a field theory or a wave theory or a particle theory\u2026 but they are only approximate concepts based on macroscopic ideas. At the quantum level, particles and waves are actually two different ways of looking at the same thing. Thinking in terms of photons usually leads to the wrong conclusions. I mented a double slit experiment. There is another problem with photons. How do the electrons know that a photon is arriving? The photon comes at the speed of light and the electron has no time to react before the photon is there. Only when you realize photons are not tiny little balls can you actually make photon theory match experiments. The photons are effectively quite large, and yet all the energy of a very large photon can be absorbed by one tiny atom. It is difficult to keep all this in mind. ",
