            "answer_text": "\u201cAre reflections of light caused by the reflection of photons? If so, what actually causes the photons to reflect since the material on the mirror would still be comprised of atoms?\u201d The answer to the first question is \u2018no.\u2019 Light, when moving, behaves like a wave. It only behaves like a particle (called the photon) when it reaches its destination and is detected. By \u201clike a particle\u201d we mean that the effect of light only happens in discrete chunks. It is misleading to think of a beam of light as a stream of photons. Your second question is vaguely \u2018how does light reflection work?\u2019 In general, when the light wave reaches the intersection of two different materials, it can be transmitted into the second material, reflected back, or both in some combination. The thing that happens arises from the need to match the waves on both sides of the boundary. Metals have loosely bound electrons that are free to move around, which is why they are good electrical conductors. This also means that they react easily to the \u201celectro-\u201d part in \u201celectromagnetic wave,\u201d and the boundary condition at the interface is that electric field should be small. (Think of it as \u201cshorted out.\u201d) Physically, this corresponds to summing the incoming wave with an outgoing wave of equal magnitude and opposite phase\u2014a reflection. ",
