            "answer_text": "I find it most helpful to think of this in terms of waves, but then again I would, since I have an alternative interpretation of quantum mechanics that I term Guidance Waves (similar to the pilot wave but slightly different.) If you think of it as a wave, then reflection must occur if the wave strikes a surface and would have a different phase velocity in that medium. It is actually a consequence of the geometric need not to self-interfere. The light does not get absorbed, assuming the medium, such as clear glass, does not have an absorber. So, why does it change velocity? Largely because there is an electric field due to the electrons around the atoms, and this electric field interacts with the oscillating electric field of the light. However, the electric field around atoms in covalent compounds tends to be very weak, the reason being that it is exactly opposed by the positive field of the nucleus. With metals, the electrons are delocalised over the whole substance, and now the light is slowed down almost to a standstill. As such, the waves are almost totally reflected and we see them as silver (unless, like copper and gold, some are absorbed.) If you take sodium, which tis similarly silver, and put immense pressure on it, besides rearranging the structural array, it forces the atoms to take up less volume and they do this by holding more firmly onto their electrons - if you like, they are squeezed back into their atoms. Th net result is the sodium becomes transparent. Electrons are so small light simply laps around them, but the electric fields are not localised like that. ",
