            "author_info": {
                "name": "Karl Brace",
                "href": "/profile/Karl-Brace"
            },
            "answer_text": "Light is an electromagnetic wave. A magnetic field will put forces on electrons. Metals (and some other materials) have electrons in their outer layers that are free to move. When an electromagnetic wave hits such a material, it sets those electrons moving back and forth at the same frequency, and those moving electrons emit their own electromagnetic waves of the same frequency. The metal has reflected the light! Why does the reflected light travel in the direction that it does? That\u2019s a more complicated question I won\u2019t address here. Note that the reason metals are good at reflecting light is the same reason that metals are good electrical conductors. Both processes rely on an abundance of free electrons. ",
